%I A327094 #35 Mar 27 2026 00:14:41
%S A327094 0,1,2,4,6,9,12,17,20,26,31
%N A327094 a(n) is the number of cells in the smallest polyomino that can contain all free n-ominoes.
%C A327094 a(n) <= n*(n - 1)/2 for n > 1, by using a right triangular polyomino with the topmost cell moved to the bottom row.
%C A327094    ##
%C A327094    ###
%C A327094    ####
%C A327094   ######
%C A327094 Conjecture: a(9) = 26, a(10) = 31, a(11) = 37, and a(12) = 43.
%C A327094 From _Peter Exley_, Mar 08 2026: (Start)
%C A327094 a(9) = 26 confirmed by exact SAT solver using PySAT/CaDiCaL. The solver uses Boolean variables for cell occupancy on an n X n grid, auxiliary variables for each valid placement of each free n-omino, a cardinality constraint for the cell count, and iterative connectivity cuts. Shape constraints (contiguous rows, exactly one full row of width n, symmetry breaking) reduce the search space. Top-down search from upper bound proves optimality: SAT at k=26 (solution exists), UNSAT at k=25 (no solution with 25 cells). All previously known terms a(0)-a(8) matched by solver.
%C A327094 The upper bound a(n) <= n*(n-1)/2 holds for n >= 4 but not for n = 2 or n = 3. (End)
%C A327094 From _Peter Exley_, Mar 23 2026: (Start)
%C A327094 a(10) = 31, proved by CP-SAT (OR-Tools) with CEGAR connectivity. SAT at k=31 on 5 X 10 grid (54.9s). UNSAT at k=30 proved on all grids satisfying the spanning bound (H+W-1 <= 30, H >= 5, W >= 10), with I-piece symmetry break. Cross-validated using CaDiCaL.
%C A327094 The optimal container for n=10 has the "staircase" structure with row widths 10, 8, 6, 4, 3 on a 5 X 10 grid.
%C A327094 Conjecture: a(n) = floor((n+1)^2/4) + 1 for n >= 9. This matches the conjectured values a(11) = 37, a(12) = 43. The formula floor((n+1)^2/4) = A002620(n+1) counts cells in the "staircase" polyomino with row widths n, n-2, n-4, ..., which is optimal for n <= 6 and n = 8 but requires one extra cell for n >= 9.
%C A327094 Observation: a(n) >= floor((n+1)^2/4) for all n, with equality for n = 0..6 and n = 8. The staircase lower bound arises because the container must span at least ceil(n/2) rows (spanning bound theorem: |P| >= H + W - 1 for connected polyomino P) and n columns (to contain the straight n-omino).
%C A327094 All optimal containers for n = 3..10 have bounding box ceiling(n/2) X n. (End)
%H A327094 Code Golf Stack Exchange, <a href="https://codegolf.stackexchange.com/q/167484/53884">Smallest region of the plane that contains all free n-ominoes</a>
%H A327094 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A327094">Solver code, data, and figures</a>, GitHub.
%e A327094 For n = 5 the smallest polyomino that contains all 5-ominos is a polyomino with a(5) = 9 cells. One such 9-omino that works is
%e A327094    ###
%e A327094   #####.
%e A327094      #
